BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:uk-irl-culture-connects-2026-27@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260713T112409Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260731
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260801
SUMMARY:Deadline: British Council Ireland: UK-IRL Culture Connects Grant 20
 26/27
DESCRIPTION:The UK-IRL Culture Connects Grant 2026/27 is a British Council 
 Ireland initiative delivered in association with Arts Council Ireland\, su
 pporting the early stages of artistic collaboration between Ireland and th
 e four UK nations through in-person exchange. It prioritises creative deve
 lopment over final outputs: research and development of new ideas\, mentor
 ship\, exploring collaborative pathways with producers or partners\, exper
 imenting with new technologies or practices\, and developing initiatives t
 hat support creative exchange. WHO: applications are made by individual ar
 tists or creative practitioners working as a bilateral partnership of one 
 individual based in Ireland and one based in England\, Northern Ireland\, 
 Scotland or Wales\; applicants must be resident in Ireland or the UK for t
 he project duration\, have a proven professional track record\, be at an e
 arly or developing career stage\, and not be in full-time education. One a
 pplication per collaboration. FUNDING: up to EUR 3\,000 covering artist an
 d collaborator fees\, travel and accommodation\, studio hire\, materials\,
  and access costs. Activities must involve in-person collaboration (fully 
 remote projects are not eligible) and take place between October 2026 and 
 31 March 2027. Apply via the British Council GoodGrants platform\; an info
 rmation webinar recording and overview document are on the programme page.
  DEADLINE: 31 July 2026.\n\nOrganisation: British Council Ireland / Arts C
 ouncil Ireland\nLocation: Ireland and the UK. For bilateral partnerships o
 f one individual based in Ireland and one based in England\, Northern Irel
 and\, Scotland or Wales\; in-person collaboration required.\nAward: Up to 
 EUR 3\,000 per collaboration (smaller amounts also eligible)\, covering ar
 tist fees (including your own time)\, collaborator fees\, travel and accom
 modation\, studio or space hire\, materials\, and access costs including d
 isability support. No application fee.\nDuration: Activity between October
  2026 and March 2027\; must be completed by 31 March 2027\n\nMore: https:/
 /www.britishcouncil.ie/programmes/arts/uk-irl-culture-connects-grant-20262
 7?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://www.britishcouncil.ie/programmes/arts/uk-irl-culture-connects-g
 rant-202627?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Ireland and the UK. For bilateral partnerships of one individual b
 ased in Ireland and one based in England\, Northern Ireland\, Scotland or 
 Wales\; in-person collaboration required.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:nebraska-arts-council-artist-fellowship-2026@artificialnouveau.github.i
 o
DTSTAMP:20260713T112409Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20261117
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20261118
SUMMARY:Deadline: Nebraska Arts Council: Individual Artist Fellowship 2026 
 (Performing Arts)
DESCRIPTION:The Nebraska Arts Council's Individual Artist Fellowship awards
  up to $5\,000 for a one-year period to support professional development: 
 creating new work\, presentations\, training and/or research. The fellowsh
 ip rotates among three umbrella categories\; the 2026 round accepts Perfor
 ming Arts applications in theater/playwriting\, choreography\, filmmaking/
 screenwriting\, and music/sound. ELIGIBILITY: Nebraska resident for at lea
 st 24 months before application\, remaining resident during the fellowship
  year (attestation required)\; 19 or older\; not enrolled in an undergradu
 ate program in the discipline applied for (graduate and certificate progra
 ms allowed)\; applicants must be the originator of the submitted work\, no
 t an interpreter. Previous winners may reapply after three years with new 
 work if prior grant requirements were completed. SUBMISSION: artist biogra
 phy\, artist statement (name redacted\; themes\, influences\, techniques)\
 , and five work samples with descriptions or synopses. Questions: meagan.d
 ion@nebraska.gov. DEADLINE: 17 November 2026.\n\nOrganisation: Nebraska Ar
 ts Council\nLocation: Nebraska\, USA. Applicants must have been Nebraska r
 esidents for at least 24 months before applying and remain residents durin
 g the fellowship year.\nAward: Up to $5\,000 for a one-year fellowship sup
 porting professional development\, including the creation of new art\, pre
 sentations\, training and/or research. No application fee.\nDuration: One-
 year fellowship period\n\nMore: https://www.artscouncil.nebraska.gov/apply
 /individual-artist-fellowship/?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_m
 edium=referral
URL:https://www.artscouncil.nebraska.gov/apply/individual-artist-fellowship
 /?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Nebraska\, USA. Applicants must have been Nebraska residents for a
 t least 24 months before applying and remain residents during the fellowsh
 ip year.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:global-artivism-governance-fellow-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260713T112409Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260716
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260717
SUMMARY:Deadline: Global Artivism: Governance Fellow
DESCRIPTION:Global Artivism\, a Global Majority-led movement that engages t
 he power of arts and culture toward a just world on a safe planet\, is con
 tracting a Governance Fellow for a mentored\, time-limited engagement focu
 sed on governance systems\, democratic institutional design\, and Global M
 ajority-led movement infrastructure. The contractor supports the developme
 nt and maintenance of Global Artivism's governance architecture\, includin
 g documentation\, committee coordination\, and research that supports the 
 Democratic Transition process\, and is expected to take initiative on assi
 gned tasks and grow through structured mentorship. The movement is governe
 d by a Global Council with a Movement Secretariat coordination team\; the 
 Fellow coordinates primarily with the Governance Lead alongside the Operat
 ions Director\, Secretariat members\, and Council committees (coordination
  relationships do not constitute supervisory authority). KEY RESPONSIBILIT
 IES: governance documentation (frameworks\, committee charters\, terms of 
 reference\, process documentation\; maintaining an organized\, current\, c
 onsistently formatted document library\; preparing materials for Global Co
 uncil meetings)\; committee coordination (scheduling\, materials\, meeting
  notes\, follow-up\, trackers of decisions and action items\, agendas and 
 briefing packs)\; Democratic Transition and electoral process support (res
 earch on governance models\, electoral processes\, and democratic particip
 ation mechanisms\; drafting materials for the Democratic Transition Roadma
 p 2025-2027\; preparing electoral framework and testing documentation\; tr
 acking milestones)\; and governance research (comparative analyses and bri
 efing notes\; staying current on distributed governance\, participatory de
 mocracy\, and decentralized leadership\; contributing to knowledge product
 s). REQUIRED: manages multiple documentation tasks and meets deadlines wit
 h attention to accuracy and formatting (experience via union organizing\, 
 participatory facilitation\, cooperative governance\, or community-based d
 ecision-making counts alongside academic or formal work history)\; good wr
 itten English\; ability to take initiative and work independently\; genuin
 e interest in governance\, movement building\, or institutional design\; a
 bility to operate as an independent contractor\; and commitment to Global 
 Artivism's values. PREFERRED: background in governance\, law\, political s
 cience\, or international development\; interest in Global Majority leader
 ship and distributed power\; civil society/NGO/movement experience\; famil
 iarity with arts\, culture\, or social justice movements\; multilingual ab
 ility in languages relevant to Global South contexts. This is an independe
 nt contractor engagement managed through Global Artivism's fiscal sponsors
 hip with Res Publica US Inc.\; the contractor sets their own hours and met
 hods\, may serve other clients\, and handles their own taxes and local com
 pliance. TO APPLY: submit an expression of interest via the ABM Intelligen
 ce application page\; submissions are reviewed on a rolling basis by ABM's
  consulting team. Expressions of interest close Thursday 16 July 2026\, 10
 pm MYT (UTC+8)\; late submissions will not be reviewed. Priority is given 
 to candidates from the Global South and Global Majority communities\, and 
 community organizing\, grassroots coordination\, and self-taught practice 
 are valued alongside formal credentials.\n\nOrganisation: Global Artivism 
 (a fiscally sponsored project of Res Publica US Inc.)\nLocation: Remote\, 
 open globally. Priority given to applicants from the Global South.\nAward:
  USD 1\,200 to 1\,800 per month (independent contractor fee)\, paid on rec
 eipt of monthly invoices. No employee benefits\, paid leave\, or insurance
 \; contractor covers their own taxes and compliance.\nDuration: 12-month i
 ndependent contractor engagement from August 2026\, with potential renewal
  subject to funding and mutual agreement. Flexible hours with scheduled ca
 lls across time zones.\n\nMore: https://www.abm-intelligence.com/governanc
 efellow-globalartivism?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=re
 ferral
URL:https://www.abm-intelligence.com/governancefellow-globalartivism?utm_so
 urce=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Remote\, open globally. Priority given to applicants from the Glob
 al South.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:global-artivism-operations-fellow-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260713T112409Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260716
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260717
SUMMARY:Deadline: Global Artivism: Operations Fellow
DESCRIPTION:Global Artivism\, a Global Majority-led movement that engages t
 he power of arts and culture toward a just world on a safe planet\, is con
 tracting an Operations Fellow for a mentored\, time-limited engagement foc
 used on organizational infrastructure and systems design. Working alongsid
 e the Operations Director\, the contractor designs operational frameworks 
 spanning financial workflows\, contractor management\, governance alignmen
 t\, and onboarding\, contributing directly to infrastructure decisions whi
 le building practical experience in how a Global Majority-led movement org
 anization functions operationally. The Fellow coordinates primarily with t
 he Operations Director alongside the Governance Lead\, Project Manager\, A
 dmin Coordinator\, and Secretariat members (coordination relationships do 
 not constitute supervisory authority\; decision-making is distributed thro
 ugh governance structures and committees). KEY RESPONSIBILITIES: infrastru
 cture design and framework development (designing and documenting operatio
 nal frameworks\; contributing to staffing models\, organizational structur
 es\, and resource frameworks that enable both centralized and decentralize
 d work\; designing onboarding and operational guidance\; aligning operatio
 nal systems with governance frameworks and democratic decision-making)\; s
 ystems and knowledge documentation (operational guidance and toolkits for 
 distributed teams\; internal knowledge systems such as documentation\, che
 cklists\, and decision trees)\; and capacity building and research (identi
 fying where documentation or systems redesign enables teams to work more i
 ndependently\; flagging operational bottlenecks and proposing solutions\; 
 sharing learning with Council\, committees\, and teams\; researching opera
 tional models relevant to Global Artivism's structure). REQUIRED: manages 
 multiple tasks and meets deadlines with attention to detail and comfort co
 ordinating logistics across a distributed team (experience via coordinatin
 g community events\, grassroots logistics\, or operations in any context c
 ounts alongside formal work history)\; good written English\; comfort with
  digital tools (Google Workspace\, Slack\, or similar)\; genuine interest 
 in operations\, organizational systems\, or movement infrastructure\; abil
 ity to operate as an independent contractor\; and commitment to Global Art
 ivism's values. PREFERRED: background in business administration\, project
  management\, or finance\; interest in international civil society\, movem
 ent building\, or Global Majority leadership\; civil society/NGO/community
  experience\; familiarity with digital project management or operations to
 ols\; multilingual ability in languages relevant to Global South contexts.
  This is an independent contractor engagement managed through Global Artiv
 ism's fiscal sponsorship with Res Publica US Inc.\; the contractor sets th
 eir own hours and methods\, may serve other clients\, and handles their ow
 n taxes and local compliance. TO APPLY: submit an expression of interest v
 ia the ABM Intelligence application page\; submissions are reviewed on a r
 olling basis by ABM's consulting team. Expressions of interest close Thurs
 day 16 July 2026\, 10pm MYT (UTC+8)\; late submissions will not be reviewe
 d. Priority is given to candidates from the Global South and Global Majori
 ty communities\, and community organizing\, grassroots coordination\, and 
 self-taught practice are valued alongside formal credentials.\n\nOrganisat
 ion: Global Artivism (a fiscally sponsored project of Res Publica US Inc.)
 \nLocation: Remote\, open globally. Priority given to applicants from the 
 Global South.\nAward: USD 1\,000 to 1\,500 per month (independent contract
 or fee)\, paid on receipt of monthly invoices. No employee benefits\, paid
  leave\, or insurance\; contractor covers their own taxes and compliance.\
 nDuration: 12-month independent contractor engagement from August 2026\, w
 ith potential renewal subject to funding and mutual agreement. Flexible ho
 urs with scheduled calls across time zones.\n\nMore: https://www.abm-intel
 ligence.com/operationsfellow-globalartivism?utm_source=artificialnouveaugr
 antdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://www.abm-intelligence.com/operationsfellow-globalartivism?utm_so
 urce=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Remote\, open globally. Priority given to applicants from the Glob
 al South.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:iias-asia-in-the-world-fellowship-2027@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260713T112409Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260910
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260911
SUMMARY:Deadline: IIAS: Asia in the World Fellowship Programme 2027-2028
DESCRIPTION:The Asia in the World Fellowship Programme\, run by the Interna
 tional Institute for Asian Studies (IIAS) at Leiden University\, is a nine
 -month\, two-phase fellowship pairing a residency at a partner institution
  in Asia\, Africa\, Latin America\, or Europe (Phase 1) with six months in
  residence at IIAS in Leiden\, the Netherlands (Phase 2). The programme su
 pports interdisciplinary\, humanities- and social-science-based research e
 ngaging Asia and its connections with the wider world. SUPPORT during the 
 Leiden phase: EUR 1\,250 per month stipend\, EUR 1\,200 per month housing 
 allowance\, and a travel grant\; the Phase 1 stipend is provided by the co
 -host institution. ELIGIBILITY: scholars and researchers worldwide\; open 
 internationally. APPLICATIONS open 1 July 2026\; deadline 10 September 202
 6. Apply via the IIAS fellowships page. NOTE: dates confirmed via secondar
 y sources at time of entry (the funder page was not directly reachable)\; 
 verify before applying.\n\nOrganisation: International Institute for Asian
  Studies (IIAS)\, Leiden University\nLocation: Two phases: a partner insti
 tution in Asia\, Africa\, Latin America\, or Europe (Phase 1)\, then Leide
 n\, Netherlands (Phase 2). Open internationally.\nAward: Leiden phase: EUR
  1\,250 per month stipend plus EUR 1\,200 per month housing allowance\, pl
 us a travel grant\; the Phase 1 stipend at the co-host institution is set 
 by that institution. No application fee.\nDuration: 9 months (two phases)\
 n\nMore: https://www.iias.asia/fellowships/asia-in-the-world?utm_source=ar
 tificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://www.iias.asia/fellowships/asia-in-the-world?utm_source=artifici
 alnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Two phases: a partner institution in Asia\, Africa\, Latin America
 \, or Europe (Phase 1)\, then Leiden\, Netherlands (Phase 2). Open interna
 tionally.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:ramdam-extended-possibilities-residency-2027@artificialnouveau.github.i
 o
DTSTAMP:20260713T112409Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260714
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260715
SUMMARY:Deadline: RAMDAM\, un centre d'art: Extended Possibilities Residenc
 y 2027
DESCRIPTION:Extended Possibilities gives artists the opportunity to work on
  site at RAMDAM\, un centre d'art for 45 days\, a long period allowing the
 m to benefit from technical support and to present ongoing work to the pub
 lic. Artists receive on-site accommodation (a collective room for the whol
 e 45 days)\, access to a well-maintained\, up-to-date technical facility\,
  a grant to support their work\, and a lump-sum allowance for travel and v
 isas. RAMDAM is an activist space supporting artists in their artistic res
 earch\; residencies are open to artists or teams engaged in creation\, res
 earch\, or experimentation\, with no obligation to produce a finished work
 : dance\, theatre\, performance\, painting\, sculpture\, drawing\, film\, 
 video\, literary writing\, screenwriting\, digital art\, and hybrid forms 
 are all welcome. The call focuses on multidisciplinary projects and resear
 ch that break down barriers between disciplines and challenge their own fi
 eld of practice\, and considerable attention is given to how the work fits
  into a social and/or political context and resonates with our times. THE 
 CALL SUPPORTS: 1 or 2 artistic teams (RAMDAM can host at most 5 artists)\;
  performing artists of all disciplines\; projects at early stages of resea
 rch-creation and/or more advanced (residencies can be writing residencies 
 and/or stage residencies). All artists must be available for the full 45 d
 ays from 1 February to 15 March 2027 and must be from eligible countries (
 EU countries\, outermost regions\, overseas countries and territories\, an
 d some non-EU countries)\; artists from mainland (hexagonal) France cannot
  apply. The working and living spaces are wheelchair accessible\, though r
 eaching RAMDAM by public transport can be difficult for disabled people\; 
 accessibility support is available via Culture Moves Europe for residents 
 with disabilities. ALLOWANCES: EUR 1\,350 per resident for subsistence\; t
 ravel allowance EUR 400 under 5\,000 km or EUR 800 from 5\,000 km (travel 
 under 600 km must be by green means of transport unless disability or isla
 nd residence requires otherwise)\; green mobility top-up EUR 400 per resid
 ent for non-plane travel over 600 km\; visa top-up EUR 120\; outermost reg
 ions/OCT top-up EUR 175\; family top-up EUR 200 per child under 18 (housin
 g capacity is limited). TO APPLY: applications in English or French\; down
 load the residency project and administrative form documents and email the
  complete application to contact@ramdamcda.org with subject line 'extended
  possibilities - 2027' (no WeTransfer\, no important information in the em
 ail body\; reduce file sizes\; a third document may be added to help under
 stand the work). Confirmation within 7 working days\; shortlisted applican
 ts have video calls with the residency committee in mid-August. Deadline: 
 Tuesday 14 July 2026\, 11:59 p.m. NOTE: the call is arbitrarily limited to
  the first 40 applications received (still open as of 1 July 2026)\, so ap
 ply early. Made possible by the European programme Culture Moves Europe.\n
 \nOrganisation: RAMDAM\, un centre d'art\nLocation: Sainte-Foy-les-Lyon (n
 ear Lyon)\, France\; open to artists legally resident in Culture Moves Eur
 ope eligible countries (EU member states\, outermost regions\, overseas co
 untries and territories\, and some non-EU countries)\; artists from mainla
 nd (hexagonal) France cannot apply\nAward: EUR 1\,350 per resident allowan
 ce for subsistence and other costs\, plus travel allowance of EUR 400 (und
 er 5\,000 km) or EUR 800 (from 5\,000 km). Top-ups: green mobility EUR 400
  per resident (600 km or more by non-plane transport)\, visa EUR 120\, out
 ermost regions/OCT EUR 175\, family EUR 200 per child under 18. On-site ac
 commodation and technical facilities provided. Supported by Culture Moves 
 Europe.\nDuration: 45 days\, 1 February to 15 March 2027\n\nMore: https://
 ramdamcda.org/actualite-ramdam/extended-possibilities-residency-call?utm_s
 ource=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://ramdamcda.org/actualite-ramdam/extended-possibilities-residency
 -call?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Sainte-Foy-les-Lyon (near Lyon)\, France\; open to artists legally
  resident in Culture Moves Europe eligible countries (EU member states\, o
 utermost regions\, overseas countries and territories\, and some non-EU co
 untries)\; artists from mainland (hexagonal) France cannot apply
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:playa-artsci-awarded-residency-2027@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260713T112409Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260630
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260701
SUMMARY:Deadline: PLAYA Art/Sci Awarded Residency 2027
DESCRIPTION:PLAYA's Art/Sci Awarded Residency brings together artists and s
 cientists for immersive\, interdisciplinary inquiry at a rural retreat nea
 r Summer Lake in Lake County\, Oregon. The 2027 cycle offers four session 
 options ranging from 11 to 25 nights between January and November 2027. Aw
 arded residents receive free lodging in a private cabin with kitchen and b
 athroom plus one weekly group meal\, while covering their own travel\, foo
 d\, and materials. Both established and emerging practitioners in any medi
 a may apply\, including naturalists\, biologists\, sound artists\, new med
 ia artists\, writers\, performers\, and interdisciplinary creators\, and a
 ll applicants must be at least 18 years old. Applications are submitted th
 rough SlideRoom and require work samples and two references. There is a US
 D 40 application fee\, though PLAYA states all fee waiver requests will be
  granted if submitted by June 28\, 2026.\n\nOrganisation: PLAYA\nLocation:
  Summer Lake\, Lake County\, Oregon\, USA\nAward: Awarded residency provid
 ing free lodging in a private cabin with kitchen and bathroom plus one wee
 kly group meal. Residents cover their own travel\, groceries\, and materia
 ls. No cash stipend. USD 40 application fee (waivers granted on request by
  June 28\, 2026)\nDuration: 11 to 25 nights depending on session\n\nMore: 
 https://playasummerlake.org/2027-artsci/?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrant
 desk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://playasummerlake.org/2027-artsci/?utm_source=artificialnouveaugr
 antdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Summer Lake\, Lake County\, Oregon\, USA
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:jentel-artist-residency-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260713T112409Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260915
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260916
SUMMARY:Deadline: Jentel Artist Residency
DESCRIPTION:The Jentel Artist Residency offers approximately three-week res
 idencies in the foothills of the Bighorn Mountains near Banner\, Wyoming\,
  giving artists\, writers\, and composers dedicated time for creative work
 . Sessions run from mid-January through early December\, hosting six resid
 ents at a time. It is open to visual artists in any medium\, writers of fi
 ction\, creative nonfiction\, or poetry\, and composers across musical gen
 res. Residents receive a private bedroom\, a separate studio\, shared livi
 ng and kitchen space\, and a USD 100 weekly stipend to help cover food and
  personal expenses. Applicants must be at least 25 years old and be U.S. c
 itizens or foreign nationals whose primary residence is in the U.S. during
  the application year\, and may not be enrolled full-time in a degree prog
 ram. There is a USD 30 non-refundable application fee\, with deadlines of 
 September 15 for Winter and Spring sessions and January 15 for Summer and 
 Fall sessions.\n\nOrganisation: Jentel Foundation\nLocation: Banner\, Wyom
 ing\, USA\nAward: USD 100 weekly stipend (about USD 300 total over three w
 eeks)\, plus private bedroom\, separate studio space\, and shared living a
 nd kitchen facilities provided at no cost USD 30 application fee\nDuration
 : Approximately 3 weeks (arrive on the 15th\, depart the morning of the 7t
 h of the following month)\n\nMore: https://www.jentelarts.org/apply?utm_so
 urce=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://www.jentelarts.org/apply?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&
 utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Banner\, Wyoming\, USA
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:simons-foundation-open-interval-turbulence-2026@artificialnouveau.githu
 b.io
DTSTAMP:20260713T112409Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20261021
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20261022
SUMMARY:Deadline: Open Interval: An Artist-Scientist Exploration of Turbule
 nce
DESCRIPTION:Open Interval is a Simons Foundation program that supports trio
 s consisting of an artist\, a scientist\, and a representative from a 501(
 c)(3) arts organization to collaborate around a shared scientific theme. T
 he current cycle centers on the theme of turbulence\, a phenomenon at the 
 edge of chaos and beauty. Awarded trios receive USD 30\,000 to support a s
 ustained period of thought partnership and exploration rather than the pro
 duction of finished works or exhibitions. The program runs from April to D
 ecember 2027 with a touchstone meeting in May 2027 and possible cohort con
 venings. Trio members must be regionally co-located anywhere in the United
  States so they can collaborate in person. The scientist should hold a Ph.
 D. and be conducting basic research\, with priority given to fields such a
 s astrophysics\, neuroscience\, quantum physics\, biology\, or mathematics
 . The application portal opens September 9\, 2026\, and all three trio mem
 bers must submit for the application to be complete.\n\nOrganisation: Simo
 ns Foundation\nLocation: United States (trio must be regionally co-located
 )\nAward: USD 30\,000 per awarded trio\nDuration: April to December 2027 (
 several months of collaboration)\n\nMore: https://www.simonsfoundation.org
 /2026/06/01/coming-soon-open-interval-an-artist-scientist-exploration-of-t
 urbulence/?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://www.simonsfoundation.org/2026/06/01/coming-soon-open-interval-a
 n-artist-scientist-exploration-of-turbulence/?utm_source=artificialnouveau
 grantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:United States (trio must be regionally co-located)
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:helene-wurlitzer-foundation-residency-2027@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260713T112409Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20270118
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20270119
SUMMARY:Deadline: Helene Wurlitzer Foundation Residency
DESCRIPTION:The Helene Wurlitzer Foundation of New Mexico runs one of the o
 ldest artist residency programs in the United States\, established in 1954
 \, on a 15-acre campus in Taos\, New Mexico. The residency is open to visu
 al artists\, literary artists\, and music composers\, including painters\,
  sculptors\, photographers\, filmmakers\, writers\, poets\, playwrights\, 
 screenwriters\, and songwriters. Selected grantees receive rent-free and u
 tility-paid housing in a furnished casita for a session of 10 to 12 weeks\
 , with access to a Commons House offering WiFi\, a library\, and bicycles.
  No stipend is provided in most cases\, and residents cover their own food
  and transportation. Applications are open to creative artists worldwide r
 egardless of age\, experience\, or nationality\, and the annual deadline i
 s January 18 for residencies the following calendar year. There is a non-w
 aivable USD 30 application fee.\n\nOrganisation: The Helene Wurlitzer Foun
 dation of New Mexico\nLocation: Taos\, New Mexico\, USA\nAward: Rent-free\
 , utility-paid furnished housing (casita)\; no stipend (rare stipend suppo
 rt via the Rhonda Artist Stipend Fund)\; artists cover food and travel USD
  30 application fee\nDuration: 10 to 12 weeks (Sessions 1 and 3 are 12 wee
 ks\, Session 2 is 10 weeks)\n\nMore: https://wurlitzerfoundation.org/apply
 ?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://wurlitzerfoundation.org/apply?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrant
 desk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Taos\, New Mexico\, USA
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:british-council-connections-through-culture-2026@artificialnouveau.gith
 ub.io
DTSTAMP:20260713T112409Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260812
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260813
SUMMARY:Deadline: Connections Through Culture Grants 2026 (British Council)
DESCRIPTION:Connections Through Culture (CTC) grants are designed to enable
  meaningful partnerships\, cross-cultural exchange and long-term collabora
 tion between the UK and participating countries. In 2026\, CTC incorporate
 s the grants programmes formerly known as Biennials Connect (Visual Arts) 
 and Architecture\, Design and Fashion Biennials and Festivals Grants\, and
  serves as the British Council's major Arts grants programme for 2026 (in 
 place of International Collaboration Grants). It offers grants of between 
 GBP 5\,000 and GBP 15\,000 to support creative practitioners\, cultural pr
 ofessionals\, artists\, organisations\, festivals\, biennials\, hubs and c
 ollectives to develop and deliver collaborative projects across a wide ran
 ge of themes and art forms\, including applied arts\, architecture\, curat
 ing\, dance\, design\, digital\, drawing\, education\, fashion\, film\, in
 stallation\, interdisciplinary work\, painting\, performance\, photography
 \, printmaking\, public art\, research\, sculpture\, social practice\, sou
 nd art\, textiles\, video\, visual arts and writing. ELIGIBILITY: applicat
 ions must involve collaboration between at least one UK-based partner and 
 at least one partner based in an eligible participating country\; each par
 tner must be legally based in the country they are applying from at the ti
 me of application and throughout the project activity period. PARTICIPATIN
 G COUNTRIES: Albania\, Argentina\, Australia\, Bangladesh\, Bosnia and Her
 zegovina\, Colombia\, Mainland China\, Egypt\, Indonesia\, Kazakhstan\, Ke
 nya\, Kosovo\, Lebanon\, Malaysia\, Mexico\, Montenegro\, New Zealand\, Ni
 geria\, North Macedonia\, Pakistan\, Palestine\, Peru\, Philippines\, Saud
 i Arabia\, Serbia\, South Africa\, Tanzania\, Thailand\, Tunisia\, Turkey\
 , United Arab Emirates\, UK\, Ukraine\, Uzbekistan\, Venezuela\, and Vietn
 am. Eligible applicants include artists and creative practitioners\, arts 
 and cultural organisations\, festivals and biennials\, cultural profession
 als\, creative hubs/networks/collectives\, and organisations working acros
 s arts\, culture and the creative sectors. Note: applications involving pr
 ojects organised by or taking place as part of Visual Arts\, Architecture\
 , Design\, Fashion and Craft festivals should be made by the festival or b
 iennial organisation rather than by individual artists\, designers or prac
 titioners. No application fee. Deadline 12 August 2026.\n\nOrganisation: B
 ritish Council\nLocation: International collaboration grant. Each applicat
 ion must involve at least one UK-based partner and at least one partner ba
 sed in an eligible participating country\; each partner must be legally ba
 sed in the country they apply from throughout the project.\nAward: Grants 
 of between GBP 5\,000 and GBP 15\,000. Free to apply.\nDuration: Project-b
 ased\; develop and deliver collaborative projects across a range of themes
  and art forms.\n\nMore: https://arts.britishcouncil.org/connections-throu
 gh-culture?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
