UID:revitalizing-rituals-2026-open-call@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260713T112409Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260719
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260720
SUMMARY:Deadline: Revitalizing Rituals 2026 Open Call
DESCRIPTION:Revitalizing Rituals invites artists from all disciplines -- so
 und\, movement\, visual arts\, installation\, performance\, and transdisci
 plinary practices -- to join a research-creation journey across two landsc
 apes: Bhar Lazreg in Tunisia and the wetlands of Somogy County in Hungary.
  The project explores rituals as living forms of belonging: reconnecting c
 ommunities\, land\, memory\, food\, ecological reciprocity\, and the more-
 than-human world. Selected artists work with local communities as co-parti
 cipants in a shared inquiry into moving from extraction toward reciprocity
 . Organised by Homo Faber Alapítvány (Hungary). AMOUNT: EUR 6\,000 gross
  artist fee and production budget\; international travel and per diems cov
 ered\; on-site accommodation provided. ELIGIBILITY: minimum 5 years of act
 ive artistic practice\; portfolio reflecting interest in situated or relat
 ional work\; no formal degree required\; working language is English (loca
 l language navigation valued)\; must be available for the full residency c
 ycle including all international travel\; must be able to legally receive 
 the fee and invoice the organising partners from country of residence. Str
 ongly encourages applications from historically marginalised or underrepre
 sented voices. KEY DATES: Application Deadline 19 July 2026 (midnight) -- 
 note the open call PDF also references a 5 July date\; the officially prom
 oted deadline is 19 July\; Online Q&A 29 June 2026\, 14:00 Tunisia / 15:00
  CET (register at https://forms.gle/brnZvXvFe4JB8zL26)\; Online Conversati
 ons with shortlisted artists: mid July to mid August 2026\; Selection Resu
 lts: 31 August 2026\; Placemaking Camp: 1 week\, end of November 2026\, Hu
 ngary\; Storytellers Camp: 1 week\, March 2027\, Tunisia\; Residency Perio
 d: minimum 1 month (splittable)\, April to July 2027\; Final Presentation:
  August 2027\; Closing Event: 3 days\, winter/early spring 2028\, Hungary.
  Apply via the open call form linked at https://homofaber.hu/wp-content/up
 loads/2026/06/Artist-Open-Call-FINAL-in-the-RR-form.pdf.\n\nOrganisation: 
 Homo Faber Alapítvány (Homo Faber Foundation)\nLocation: Bhar Lazreg\, T
 unisia and Somogy County\, Hungary\; multi-stage in-person residency acros
 s both sites.\nAward: EUR 6\,000 gross artist fee and production budget\; 
 international travel and per diems covered\; on-site accommodation provide
 d. No application fee.\nDuration: Multi-stage residency: Placemaking Camp 
 (1 week\, November 2026\, Hungary)\; Storytellers Camp (1 week\, March 202
 7\, Tunisia)\; Residency Period (minimum 1 month\, April-July 2027)\; publ
 ic presentation (August 2027)\; Closing Event (3 days\, winter/early sprin
 g 2028\, Hungary).\n\nMore: https://homofaber.hu/wp-content/uploads/2026/0
 6/Artist-Open-Call-FINAL-in-the-RR-form.pdf?utm_source=artificialnouveaugr
 antdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://homofaber.hu/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/Artist-Open-Call-FINAL-
 in-the-RR-form.pdf?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referr
 al
LOCATION:Bhar Lazreg\, Tunisia and Somogy County\, Hungary\; multi-stage in
 -person residency across both sites.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:prohelvetia-reflection-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260713T112409Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260901
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260902
SUMMARY:Deadline: Reflection (All Disciplines)
DESCRIPTION:Reflection is a Pro Helvetia grant supporting collective mediat
 ion projects that use innovative formats to foster critical reflection on 
 artistic practice and cultural transformation\, across all supported disci
 plines (design\, literature\, music\, performing arts\, visual arts\, and 
 innovation and society). Open to collectives comprising at least two cultu
 ral practitioners (artists\, creatives\, cultural practitioners\, or art e
 ducators)\; solo projects are excluded. ELIGIBILITY: requires a connection
  to Switzerland (Swiss citizenship\, or permanent residency with regular a
 rtistic activity in Switzerland)\; not open to practitioners without a Swi
 ss connection. For international collaborations\, at least 50 percent of p
 ractitioners must be from Switzerland. AMOUNT: maximum CHF 25\,000\, and n
 o more than 50 percent of the total budget. Deadlines twice a year: 1 Marc
 h (23:59 CET) and 1 September (23:59 CEST). Apply via the Pro Helvetia por
 tal.\n\nOrganisation: Pro Helvetia (Swiss Arts Council)\nLocation: Collect
 ives of at least two cultural practitioners\; for international collaborat
 ions at least 50 percent must be from Switzerland.\nAward: Maximum CHF 25\
 ,000 (cannot exceed 50 percent of total budget). No application fee.\nDura
 tion: Collective mediation project fostering critical reflection\; deadlin
 es twice yearly (1 March and 1 September).\n\nMore: https://prohelvetia.ch
 /en/find-support/reflection?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medi
 um=referral
URL:https://prohelvetia.ch/en/find-support/reflection?utm_source=artificial
 nouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Collectives of at least two cultural practitioners\; for internati
 onal collaborations at least 50 percent must be from Switzerland.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:hibrides-biennial-artistic-research-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260713T112409Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260907
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260908
SUMMARY:Deadline: Híbrides: Small Embodied Data - Call for Contributions (
 2nd Edition)
DESCRIPTION:Híbrides is a biennial of artistic research co-organised by th
 e Axolot.cat collective and the DARTS (Design\, Art\, Technology and Socie
 ty) research group at the UOC in Barcelona. The second edition\, "Small Em
 bodied Data\," centres on the concept of classification -- approached thro
 ugh machine learning\, data science\, algorithmic systems\, and questions 
 of who designs classifiers\, under what ethical codes\, and to what end. T
 he biennial brings classification into dialogue with its previous themes o
 f Small Data (community-defined\, intentional data collection and analysis
 ) and Embodiment (bodily experience as a foundation of situated\, sensory 
 knowledge). Both academic and non-academic contributions are welcome. FORM
 ATS ACCEPTED: Oral Presentations (20 minutes\; artistic practice\, artisti
 c research\, or academic research projects\; may be video-recorded for a p
 ublic archive and developed into short papers)\; Performances (20-30 minut
 es\; must engage with the physical body\, stage\, and technology\; complet
 e works\, including previously presented work\; takes place in a multipurp
 ose space with technical support). SUBMISSION REQUIREMENTS: online form wi
 th abstract (max 1\,000 characters)\, professional biography (max 1\,000 c
 haracters)\, and link to representative materials (3-5 images\; video and 
 technical rider required for performances). HONORARIA: oral presentations 
 €100\; performances €400\; invoice required in both cases. Participant
 s must follow the event's code of conduct. Event runs 26-28 November 2026 
 at UOC Poblenou campus and Convent de Sant Agustí\, Barcelona. Deadline: 
 7 September 2026. Submit at https://hibrides.axolot.cat/opencall.html.\n\n
 Organisation: Axolot.cat collective and DARTS research group\, Universitat
  Oberta de Catalunya (UOC)\nLocation: Barcelona\, Spain\; UOC Poblenou cam
 pus and Convent de Sant Agustí. In-person attendance required.\nAward: Or
 al presentations: €100 honorarium (invoice required). Performances: €4
 00 honorarium (invoice required). No submission fee.\nDuration: Festival r
 uns 26-28 November 2026.\n\nMore: https://hibrides.axolot.cat/opencall.htm
 l?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://hibrides.axolot.cat/opencall.html?utm_source=artificialnouveaug
 rantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Barcelona\, Spain\; UOC Poblenou campus and Convent de Sant Agust
 í. In-person attendance required.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:democracy-stories-lab-open-call-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260713T112409Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260914
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260915
SUMMARY:Deadline: Democracy Stories Lab: Open Call for Visual Storytellers
DESCRIPTION:The Democracy Stories Lab\, an initiative of People Powered (a 
 global hub for participatory democracy) in partnership with the Democracy 
 Narratives Alliance\, invites creators worldwide to submit visual content 
 -- short videos\, illustrations\, or graphics -- that tells a compelling s
 tory about democracy\, voice\, fairness\, belonging\, and community power.
  Content can be original or already published\, as long as it is the appli
 cant's own work and engages with narrative frameworks from the Democracy N
 arratives Alliance's research on 'How to Talk About Democracy.' Tone is op
 en\; serious and comedic approaches are both welcome. AWARDS: 4 winning en
 tries receive USD $1\,000 each\; 5 honorable mentions receive USD $500 eac
 h\; all winners receive amplification across People Powered and Democracy 
 Narratives Alliance communications networks and are featured in a global s
 creening event. WHO CAN APPLY: individual creators and small teams anywher
 e in the world\; especially welcomes creators who reach audiences outside 
 usual democracy circles\, who come from communities traditionally with les
 s of a say in public discourse\, and who work in civic tech\, advocacy\, c
 ommunity organising\, comedy\, art\, illustration\, games\, or lifestyle c
 ontent. Applications open 14 July 2026 via the Democracy Stories Lab page 
 at https://www.peoplepowered.org/news-content/announcing-the-democracy-sto
 ries-lab\; subscribe to the People Powered newsletter to be notified when 
 the form opens. Submission deadline: 14 September 2026. Winners announced 
 October-November 2026. Note: the initiative was itself voted into existenc
 e through People Powered's participatory budgeting process (PP Decides).\n
 \nOrganisation: People Powered and Democracy Narratives Alliance\nLocation
 : Worldwide\; remote. Global screening event for winners.\nAward: USD $1\,
 000 for each of 4 winners\; USD $500 for each of 5 honorable mentions. Plu
 s amplification across People Powered and Democracy Narratives Alliance ne
 tworks and feature in a global screening event. No application fee.\nDurat
 ion: One-time award.\n\nMore: https://www.peoplepowered.org/news-content/a
 nnouncing-the-democracy-stories-lab?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&
 utm_medium=referral
URL:https://www.peoplepowered.org/news-content/announcing-the-democracy-sto
 ries-lab?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Worldwide\; remote. Global screening event for winners.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:new-inc-year-13-mentor-open-call-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260713T112409Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260708
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260709
SUMMARY:Deadline: NEW INC Year 13 Mentor Open Call
DESCRIPTION:NEW INC\, the New Museum's cultural incubator\, is seeking ment
 ors for Year 13 of its program supporting creative practitioners at the in
 tersection of art\, design\, and technology. This is a call for mentors (c
 reative and business leaders)\, not for program members. TWO MENTOR TYPES:
  Dedicated Mentors ($500 honorarium) are matched one-on-one with a member 
 and commit to ongoing support throughout the year\; Office Hours Mentors (
 $300 honorarium) offer one-on-one sessions to the broader community on an 
 as-needed basis. All mentors receive a one-year All Access Plus membership
  to the New Museum\, invitations to special events including the annual DE
 MO Festival\, and access to community-only workshops\, talks\, and social 
 events. YEAR 13 PROGRAM TRACKS mentors may support: Art & Code\; Creative 
 Science\; Extended Realities\; Launchpad\; Social Architecture. KEY DATES:
  Mentor Open Call closes 8 July 2026\; Mentor Open House (virtual info ses
 sion) 17 June 2026\, 12-1pm ET (register via the site)\; mandatory Dedicat
 ed Mentor matchmaking ranking session 11 September 2026\; mandatory Dedica
 ted Mentor matchmaking event 18 September 2026\; Dedicated Mentor matches 
 announced 2 October 2026. Most NEW INC activities take place Monday-Friday
 \, 10am-6pm ET. Apply at https://www.newmuseum.org/new-inc/open-call/.\n\n
 Organisation: NEW INC (New Museum Incubator)\nLocation: New York\, NY\, US
 A\; primarily in-person at 250 Hudson St\, lower Manhattan. Some hybrid pa
 rticipation possible.\nAward: Dedicated Mentors: $500 honorarium. Office H
 ours Mentors: $300 honorarium. All mentors also receive a one-year All Acc
 ess Plus membership to the New Museum. No application fee.\nDuration: Year
  13 program (September 2026 onward)\; average 4-8 hours of engagement per 
 week.\n\nMore: https://www.newmuseum.org/new-inc/open-call/?utm_source=art
 ificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://www.newmuseum.org/new-inc/open-call/?utm_source=artificialnouve
 augrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:New York\, NY\, USA\; primarily in-person at 250 Hudson St\, lower
  Manhattan. Some hybrid participation possible.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:jamverse-jam-protocolized-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260713T112409Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260731
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260801
SUMMARY:Deadline: Jamverse Jam (Protocolized worldbuilding contest)
DESCRIPTION:Protocolized's fourth contest invites artists and writers (stor
 ytellers\, poets\, comic artists) to build\, extend\, and connect the Jamv
 erse\, a shared near-future science fiction universe of four intersecting 
 story cycles (The Stockton Chronicles\, Legends and Ledgers\, UET-Trainver
 se\, and Zoothesia). ELIGIBILITY: open to anyone\; you may submit up to th
 ree in-universe worldbuilding artifacts\, and the same creator can win mul
 tiple prizes. REQUIREMENTS: each artifact must be under 1\,000 words (200-
 700 is the sweet spot) or a visual equivalent (comic panel\, poster\, adve
 rtisement\, etc.) and must include at least one element drawn from one of 
 the four sub-world 'toy boxes'\, a surprising 'traffic jam' (an emergent\,
  ah-ha consequence of a technology or protocol)\, and a relation to the th
 eme of Stigmergy (indirect coordination through modifying a shared environ
 ment). Artifact types can include comic panels\, job postings\, poems\, fo
 rum threads\, historic documents\, or encyclopedia entries. APPLY: submit 
 each artifact as a public Google Doc via the contest form\, including the 
 artifact\, a one-paragraph explanation of the worlds/toy-box components us
 ed and how the piece relates to stigmergy and explores a traffic jam\, and
 \, if AI was used\, documentation of your AI/LLM protocol. PRIZES: one USD
  1\,000 grand prize and at least 10 USD 200 prizes\, all published on the 
 Jamverse website. DEADLINE: 31 July 2026. Contest rules\, the current Jamv
 erse stories\, and starter materials are on the Jamverse website.\n\nOrgan
 isation: Protocolized (Summer of Protocols)\nLocation: Online / Worldwide\
 nAward: One USD 1\,000 grand prize plus at least 10 additional USD 200 pri
 zes\; winning artifacts are published on the Jamverse website. No entry fe
 e.\nDuration: One-off contest\; submit up to three artifacts by 31 July 20
 26\n\nMore: https://protocolized.summerofprotocols.com/p/jamverse-jam?utm_
 source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://protocolized.summerofprotocols.com/p/jamverse-jam?utm_source=ar
 tificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Online / Worldwide
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:ucross-general-residency-spring-2027@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260713T112409Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260715
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260716
SUMMARY:Deadline: Ucross General Residency (All Disciplines): Spring 2027
DESCRIPTION:Ucross offers fully funded artist residencies on a working catt
 le ranch in the foothills of Wyoming's Bighorn Mountains\, providing unint
 errupted time and space free from the pressures and distractions of daily 
 life. Founded in 1981 with its first residency period in 1983\, Ucross hos
 ts approximately 115 individuals per year. Residencies range from two to s
 ix weeks\; at any one time up to ten people are in residence\, typically f
 our writers\, four visual artists\, and two composers. Each artist receive
 s living accommodations\, meals\, and work space at no charge. Lunches and
  dinners are prepared Monday to Friday by a professional chef (lunches del
 ivered to studios\, group dinners at 6 p.m.)\, with ample provisions for b
 reakfasts and weekends\; towels\, linens\, and weekly housekeeping are pro
 vided\, and there is cell service and wireless internet throughout. Reside
 nts provide their own working materials and arrange their own travel to Sh
 eridan\, Wyoming. The program is open to visual artists\, writers\, compos
 ers\, choreographers\, interdisciplinary artists\, performance artists\, a
 nd collaborative teams\; applicants must exhibit professional standing in 
 their field\, and both established and emerging artists are encouraged to 
 apply. Applications are submitted by discipline category: dance\, music/so
 und\, performance\, film/video\, playwriting/screenwriting\, visual art\, 
 fiction\, nonfiction\, poetry\, or interdisciplinary. The work sample and 
 project proposal are the most significant features of the application and 
 should correspond to one another\; if your work is in a single discipline\
 , select the category that best fits your project\, and apply under interd
 isciplinary only if the project genuinely combines multiple disciplines. W
 ork-sample requirements by category: DANCE\, 2-3 video files (each up to 8
  minutes and 200 MB\, or up to 3 Vimeo links\, with a timestamp if longer 
 than 8 minutes)\; MUSIC/SOUND\, 3-5 audio files (each up to 8 minutes and 
 200 MB\, or up to 3 Vimeo links\; musical scores welcome)\; PERFORMANCE an
 d FILM/VIDEO\, 1-3 video files (each up to 5 minutes and under 200 MB\, or
  up to 3 Vimeo/YouTube links\, with a timestamp if longer than 5 minutes)\
 ; PLAYWRITING/SCREENWRITING\, one complete play double-spaced noting the 2
 0-page section to read\; VISUAL ART\, 10 images at 4x6 inches and 300 dpi 
 (JPG or TIF\, no PDFs) plus a data sheet listing title\, medium\, size\, a
 nd year\; FICTION and NONFICTION\, 20 pages of double-spaced writing\; POE
 TRY\, 6-10 poems (10 maximum) in one PDF\, each poem starting on a new pag
 e\, total not exceeding 15 pages\; INTERDISCIPLINARY\, samples representin
 g the genres you plan to work in\, combining any of the above. All written
  work samples must be in English. There is a USD 40 application fee. The o
 pen call for the Spring 2027 session is open May 1 to July 15\, 2026 (appl
 y by 11:59 p.m. MT on July 15). Dedicated Fellowships for Native American 
 Visual Artists and Writers and a separate Culinary Residency are also offe
 red.\n\nOrganisation: Ucross Foundation\nLocation: Sheridan\, Wyoming\, US
 A\nAward: No charge for the residency\; living accommodations\, meals\, an
 d work space provided. USD 40 application fee.\nDuration: Spring session (
 February through early June 2027)\; residencies range from two to six week
 s\n\nMore: https://www.ucrossfoundation.org/residency-program.html?utm_sou
 rce=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://www.ucrossfoundation.org/residency-program.html?utm_source=arti
 ficialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Sheridan\, Wyoming\, USA
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:effea-call-5-get-ready-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260713T112409Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20261103
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20261104
SUMMARY:Deadline: EFFEA Call #5: European Festivals Fund for Emerging Artis
 ts
DESCRIPTION:The European Festivals Fund for Emerging Artists (EFFEA)\, an i
 nitiative of the European Festivals Association co-funded by the European 
 Union\, will open its fifth call from 1 September to 3 November 2026\, wit
 h full guidelines and application details published on 1 September 2026. C
 all #5 will again support around 50 cross-border co-production residencies
  taking place in 2027\, each bringing together at least three festivals fr
 om different eligible countries to accompany an emerging artist or collect
 ive. EFFEA is a co-production residency scheme: festivals join forces acro
 ss borders to support an emerging artist through a process of creation and
  presentation\, providing dedicated time\, space\, and tailored mentoring\
 , exchange\, and collaboration\, moving beyond a single invitation toward 
 a shared artistic development journey. Each supported project is built aro
 und one leading festival working with at least two partner festivals based
  in different eligible countries\; one emerging artist or collective at th
 e centre\; a combination of artistic development\, mentoring\, exchange\, 
 and audience engagement based on the artist's needs\; and presentations or
  outcomes shared across the partner festivals. Two residency formats are o
 ffered. DISCOVERY (EUR 8\,000 grant): the proposal must include a workshop
  (live or online) hosted by the leading festival with at least one program
 mer from each partner festival\, and a work-in-progress presentation at th
 e leading festival. SPRINGBOARD (EUR 15\,000 grant): the proposal must inc
 lude final presentations or production results shown within each festival 
 (minimum the leading festival plus two partners) and a live masterclass le
 d by the artist(s) at each festival (minimum the leading festival plus two
  partners). WHO CAN APPLY: festivals that have existed for at least one ed
 ition and are registered on FestivalFinder.eu\; the festivals apply on beh
 alf of the residency project. Residency projects must fall within these ar
 tistic fields: architecture\, ballet\, contemporary dance\, circus\, desig
 n/applied arts\, digital arts\, film\, folklore and folk arts\, heritage\,
  interdisciplinary\, literature\, music\, opera\, street art\, theatre\, p
 hotography/video\, puppetry\, sculpture\, painting. A series of EFFEA info
 \, networking\, and Q&A sessions runs on Tuesdays 11:00-12:00 CEST (15 Sep
 tember\, 29 September\, 13 October\, and 20 October 2026) to help applican
 ts navigate the process and find partners. Across Calls #1 to #4\, EFFEA h
 as supported 619 festivals and 200 artists/collectives across Europe and b
 eyond.\n\nOrganisation: European Festivals Association (EFA)\nLocation: Ac
 ross eligible European countries\; residencies built around partner festiv
 als registered on FestivalFinder.eu\nAward: Per-residency grants: EUR 8\,0
 00 (Discovery format) or EUR 15\,000 (Springboard format)\nDuration: Resid
 encies take place in 2027\; call open 1 September to 3 November 2026\, ful
 l guidelines published 1 September 2026\n\nMore: https://www.effea.eu/news
 /item/2026/06/24/effea-call-5-get-ready?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantd
 esk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://www.effea.eu/news/item/2026/06/24/effea-call-5-get-ready?utm_so
 urce=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Across eligible European countries\; residencies built around part
 ner festivals registered on FestivalFinder.eu
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:rijkscultuurfondsen-interdisciplinary-grant-2026@artificialnouveau.gith
 ub.io
DTSTAMP:20260713T112409Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20261001
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20261002
SUMMARY:Deadline: Rijkscultuurfondsen: Interdisciplinary Grant
DESCRIPTION:The Interdisciplinary grant is a new joint scheme of the six Du
 tch national cultural funds (Mondriaan Fund\, Performing Arts Fund NL\, Fu
 nd for Cultural Participation\, Netherlands Film Fund\, Creative Industrie
 s Fund NL\, and the Dutch Foundation for Literature)\, announced on 7 July
  2026. It supports makers and organisations whose work genuinely crosses t
 he boundaries of the individual funds' disciplines (visual art\, design\, 
 film\, literature\, performing arts\, and cultural participation) and cann
 ot be contained within a single discipline. TWO TRACKS: an Individual trac
 k for professional makers with a demonstrable interdisciplinary practice (
 at least one year of experience\; income cap EUR 55\,000 including the gra
 nt\; approximately EUR 24\,900 for 12 months)\; and an Organisation track 
 for organisations running multi-discipline projects. AMOUNT: EUR 12\,500 t
 o 50\,000 per project. ELIGIBILITY: makers and organisations based in the 
 Netherlands or the Caribbean part of the Kingdom. APPLYING: handled throug
 h the Mondriaan Fund's online application portal (info@mondriaanfonds.nl)\
 ; an account is required in advance. DEADLINE: 1 October 2026\, 16:00 Dutc
 h time (single application round).\n\nOrganisation: Dutch national cultura
 l funds (Rijkscultuurfondsen)\, via the Mondriaan Fund\nLocation: Netherla
 nds. For professional makers and organisations based in the Netherlands or
  the Caribbean part of the Kingdom whose practice spans multiple disciplin
 es.\nAward: EUR 12\,500 to 50\,000 per project. The individual-maker track
  is approximately EUR 24\,900 for 12 months (income cap EUR 55\,000 includ
 ing the grant).\nDuration: Up to 12 months for the individual-maker track.
 \n\nMore: https://www.mondriaanfonds.nl/en/apply-for-a-grant/grants/interd
 isciplinary/?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://www.mondriaanfonds.nl/en/apply-for-a-grant/grants/interdiscipli
 nary/?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Netherlands. For professional makers and organisations based in th
 e Netherlands or the Caribbean part of the Kingdom whose practice spans mu
 ltiple disciplines.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:ecoslay-mag-02-urban-issue-open-call-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260713T112409Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260713
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260714
SUMMARY:Deadline: Ecoslay Mag: Open Call for Contributions\, Issue 02 "The 
 Urban Issue"
DESCRIPTION:Ecoslay Mag invites contributions for the second print issue of
  Ecoslay\, "The Urban Issue\," exploring the city as a space where interse
 ctional ecological futures are negotiated\, contested\, resisted\, and rei
 nvented. In the Ecoslay way\, pop culture and its influence are analysed a
 nd hijacked to communicate socio-ecological issues and ignite systemic cha
 nge: what happens when climate politics meets internet culture\, urban eco
 logy meets reality TV\, and sustainability discourse collides with camp\, 
 irony\, humour\, and memes. FORMATS (including but not limited to): essays
 \, interviews\, science communication\, poems\, visual art\, documentation
  of (art)works\, and fiction. TOPICS: urban climate communication through 
 humour\, memes\, and pop culture\; greenwashing\, eco-branding\, and susta
 inable aesthetics in urban contexts\; urban farming\, more-than-human life
 \, housing crises\, displacement and green gentrification\, class and the 
 city\, maintenance and care work in relation to urbanism\, urban environme
 ntal justice\, and community organizing\, and how these relate to pop cult
 ure\; and reflections on what Ecoslay means in an age of overlapping crise
 s. COMMITMENT: selected participants deliver one contribution to Issue 02 
 and attend two online workshops with the editorial team and fellow contrib
 utors for communal exchange and feedback on proposals and works-in-progres
 s. WHAT'S OFFERED: financial compensation for selected contributions\, edi
 torial support\, and edition\, proofreading\, and graphic design handled b
 y the team. TIMELINE: open call closes 13 July 2026\; selected contributor
 s announced approx. 15 August 2026\; work on contributions approx. 1 Septe
 mber 2026 to 10 January 2027\; contributor workshop approx. 15 September 2
 026\; final contribution deadline approx. 10 January 2027. HOW TO APPLY: s
 ubmit via the Google form. Questions via ecoslay@protonmail.com or Instagr
 am DM @ecoslay_mag.\n\nOrganisation: Ecoslay Mag\nLocation: Remote / inter
 national. Two online workshops with the editorial team\; contributions del
 ivered remotely.\nAward: Financial compensation for selected contributions
  (amount unspecified). Editorial support\, proofreading\, and graphic desi
 gn provided. No application fee.\nDuration: Contributions developed approx
 . 1 September 2026 to 10 January 2027\, with two online workshops (first a
 round 15 September 2026). Final contribution deadline approx. 10 January 2
 027.\n\nMore: https://ecoslay-mag.com/?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantde
 sk&utm_medium=referral#open-call
URL:https://ecoslay-mag.com/?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medi
 um=referral#open-call
LOCATION:Remote / international. Two online workshops with the editorial te
 am\; contributions delivered remotely.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:chornobyl40-open-call-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260713T112409Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260712
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260713
SUMMARY:Deadline: Chornobyl40: Open Call 2026 (Virtual Residency & Internat
 ional Exhibition)
DESCRIPTION:Chornobyl40 is a European artistic program\, funded by the Euro
 pean Union\, exploring the multiple legacies of the Chornobyl disaster not
  only as a past event but as an ongoing condition shaping the present and 
 future. The open call invites artists\, designers\, researchers\, collecti
 ves\, and interdisciplinary/hybrid practitioners to engage with Chornobyl 
 as a landscape\, a memory\, a political reality\, and a speculative horizo
 n. This is a call for interpretation\, friction\, and critical imagination
 \, not illustration. STRUCTURE (three phases): PHASE 1\, VIRTUAL RESIDENCY
 : 40 selected participants\, September-October 2026\, online\, weekly sess
 ions (Tuesdays 14:00-18:00 CET)\, 30 hours total with minimum 90% attendan
 ce\; a structured process from idea to concept to pre-production including
  talks on Chornobyl\, ecology\, and contaminated territories\, encounters 
 with artists and technologists\, a Concept Creation Hackathon\, an XR Conc
 ept Development Workshop (exploratory\, non-technical)\, a Mental Health &
  Eco-Anxiety Lab (4h)\, collective discussions\, peer feedback\, and tailo
 red mentoring. PHASE 2\, SELECTION & PRODUCTION: 20 projects selected (bas
 ed on a video presentation\, project documentation\, and a live pitch) rec
 eive production support. PHASE 3\, EXHIBITIONS: the 20 projects tour a Eur
 opean exhibition in 2027 (Madrid\, Berlin\, Toulouse\, Kyiv)\; artist pres
 ence optional but encouraged. WHAT'S OFFERED: for the 40 participants\, ac
 cess to a curated residency\, talks\, workshops\, mentoring\, and a Europe
 an network\; for the 20 selected projects\, a EUR 500 grant (fully digital
  works) or EUR 1\,000 grant (installations needing physical materials) plu
 s exhibition inclusion (travel\, accommodation\, and transport not covered
 ). WHO CAN APPLY: artists\, designers\, researchers\, collectives\, and in
 terdisciplinary/hybrid practices\; open internationally\, no age limit\, e
 merging and established profiles equally encouraged. PROJECT THEMES: ecolo
 gy and post-disaster environments\, memory and trauma\, geopolitical narra
 tives\, invisible forces (radiation\, data\, systems)\, technological imag
 inaries\, nuclear energy\, and misinformation and perception\; projects mu
 st relate to Chornobyl (directly or indirectly)\, be adaptable to multiple
  exhibition contexts\, and consider eco-responsibility\; new and adapted e
 xisting works both welcome. SELECTION CRITERIA (equally weighted): artisti
 c quality\, relevance to the manifesto\, eco-responsibility\, digital dime
 nsion\, and emotional and critical impact. TIMELINE: open call launched 19
  May 2026\; application deadline 12 July 2026\; 40 participants announced 
 end of July 2026. HOW TO APPLY: submit in English via the Google Form with
  a bio/CV link\, portfolio link\, and a project proposal (PDF\, 2 A4 pages
  maximum). Application is free. Questions: contact@gate22.net.\n\nOrganisa
 tion: Chornobyl40 (gate22 / European Institute of Chornobyl consortium)\nL
 ocation: Online residency (weekly sessions Tuesdays 14:00-18:00 CET)\; Eur
 opean touring exhibition 2027 in Madrid\, Berlin\, Toulouse\, and Kyiv. Op
 en internationally.\nAward: Residency is free to attend. For the 20 projec
 ts selected for production: EUR 500 grant for fully digital works or EUR 1
 \,000 grant for installations requiring physical materials\, plus inclusio
 n in the international exhibition. Travel\, accommodation\, and transport 
 are not covered. No application fee.\nDuration: Phase 1 virtual residency 
 September-October 2026 (weekly Tuesday sessions\, 30 hours total\, minimum
  90% attendance). Phase 2 selection and production. Phase 3 European touri
 ng exhibition in 2027.\n\nMore: https://forms.gle/5btrxy7LwfY8QyFW6?utm_so
 urce=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://forms.gle/5btrxy7LwfY8QyFW6?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantde
 sk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Online residency (weekly sessions Tuesdays 14:00-18:00 CET)\; Euro
 pean touring exhibition 2027 in Madrid\, Berlin\, Toulouse\, and Kyiv. Ope
 n internationally.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:national-gallery-iceland-cusp-residency-reykjavik-2027@artificialnouvea
 u.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260713T112409Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260903
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260904
SUMMARY:Deadline: National Gallery of Iceland: CUSP Artist Residency (Reykj
 avik 2027)
DESCRIPTION:The National Gallery of Iceland announces an artist residency o
 pen call under its CUSP program\, a European cooperation project funded th
 rough Creative Europe's Culture grant. Artists working in complex media or
  emerging technologies (e.g. generative AI\, custom sensors\, sound\, soft
 ware-based\, blockchain\, physical and digital hybrid) are invited to appl
 y. This is the first of four residency stays offered to different artists 
 through the program\, one in each of the participating countries (Iceland\
 , Norway\, Czechia\, and Ukraine)\, followed by two micro residencies in t
 he Netherlands and Iceland. The programme brings together artists working 
 in time-based media with museum professionals\, conservators\, and technol
 ogy specialists developing preservation and conservation methodologies to 
 ensure the long-term endurance of artworks. The selected artist will meet 
 with a preservation specialist or conservator specializing in time-based m
 edia art for an in-depth artist interview addressing the preservation need
 s of their medium\, and will present their body of work and working method
 s publicly during an open-lab masterclass designed in collaboration with t
 he museum. RESIDENCY: up to four weeks in early 2027 in Reykjavik\, exact 
 dates arranged with the selected artist. WHAT IS PROVIDED: accommodation a
 nd working space\; a travel and subsistence stipend\; an artist fee for th
 e open lab/masterclass\; and possibly hardware and software depending on t
 he artist's request and museum means. ELIGIBILITY: international artists b
 ased outside Iceland\; applicants must be residents of any of the 27 EU me
 mber states or of non-EU countries with association agreements (EFTA/EEA m
 embers\, acceding countries\, candidate countries\, and European Neighbour
 hood Policy countries). APPLICATION: complete the application form with fu
 ll name\, country of residence\, gender identity\, contact information\, a
 n artistic statement (max 2500 characters)\, a motivation letter (max 2500
  characters)\, a draft idea of the public workshop or masterclass (max 100
 0 characters)\, links to social media/professional websites\, and a CV and
  portfolio upload (max 10MB each). DEADLINE: 3 September 2026 at 23:59 GMT
 . ABOUT CUSP: Creative Understanding\, Saving and Preserving Time-Based Me
 dia Art is a transnational cooperation project co-funded by the EU's Creat
 ive Europe Culture grant\, led by the National Gallery of Iceland with Nas
 jonalmuseet (Norway)\, LI-MA (Netherlands)\, Vasulka Kitchen (Czechia)\, a
 nd Mystetskyi Art Arsenal (Ukraine)\, focused on preserving and presenting
  time-based media art. Inquiries: cusp.residency.is [at] gmail.com.\n\nOrg
 anisation: National Gallery of Iceland (Listasafn Islands)\, CUSP project\
